<h1>The Framework</h1>

<p>The named parts of the practice, rendered as the documents that define them. The
narrative spine is the <strong>Kamae chain</strong>—six links: four framing documents
carry a project from opinions to a sequence, a fifth carries each working session, and a
sixth remembers the build between them. It is the obviously-right order, never a locked
door.</p>

<figure class="chain-figure">
  {# §6 scale honesty: emit BOTH static SVGs and CSS-toggle on the rendered column width.
     Below a 480 px column the full diagram would have to shrink past legibility, so we show
     §6's header-scale chain instead of scaling the full one down. The header variant carries
     no per-node door targets by frozen definition (chain.header() takes no links), so the
     whole compact diagram links to the full chain's position on this page (#kamae-chain). #}
  <div class="chain-full" id="kamae-chain">
    {% chainSvg "full", corpus.chainLinks %}
  </div>
  <a class="chain-header-link" href="#kamae-chain" aria-label="The Kamae chain — six links: four framing documents, a pre-action document per session, and the living State Memory">
    {% chainSvg "header" %}
  </a>
  <figcaption class="caption">Four thinking documents narrow a project—its opinions, then its
  decisions, then its scope, then its sequence—into a fifth that a working session carries out,
  and a sixth that remembers where the build is between sessions.
  When an arrow loops back, an earlier document is being revised because later work taught you
  something; the change is always written down, never made silently. The mark on the per-ho
  document is where the plan becomes a single bounded step—a
  <button type="button" class="term" data-term="ho" aria-expanded="false">ho</button>—small
  enough to pick up and finish. Each box opens the document that defines it.</figcaption>
</figure>

